   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
         <opener><dateline><date when="1917-02-16">Feb. 16,1917</dateline></date>
             <salute>Dear <persName key="harriet_monroe">Harriet</persName>:</salute></opener>  
            <p>I have not the ghost of an idea who sent that scurrilous valentine, nor do I know to what occasion it refers. I remember none on which I contradicted anybody or interrupted anybody. It is quite likely that I may, at some time or other, have used <quote type="english">“I”</quote> and <quote type="english">“me”</quote> wrongly. One is apt to do such things in the heat of talk. In fact, I hardly know any one in <placeName key="new_york">New York</placeName> who uses <quote type="english">“will”</quote> and <quote type="english">“shall”</quote> correctly. I understand that the valentine has been circulated widely among poets and people interested in poetry. I only hope that such cutting below the belt will reflect disagreeably on the perpetrator.</p>
         <closer>Affectinately yours,</closer>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
